The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, February 17, 2004 				 Liberty forays into retail market
 A STAFF REPORTER																								Calcutta, Feb. 16: The Liberty group is diversifying into retail business and plans to open 24 exclusive retail outlets across the country in the next 18 months. These outlets will be managed and run by Liberty.																								Six outlets will come up by March this year, says Adarsh Gupta, executive director of Liberty. These stores will sell not only Liberty footwear but also fashion accessories, travel goods and leather clothes, he added. The first outlet will be in Mumbai and the sixth at Forum in Calcutta.																								The group has floated a new company  Liberty Retail Revolution Limited  to manage the Revolution brand of exclusive stores. The parent company has a 51 per cent stake in the retail venture while promoters hold the rest.																								We are expecting a revenue of Rs 70 crore within two years after all the stores are operational, says Gupta. The company will invest around Rs 25 crore in setting up the exclusive outlets.																								After the first six outlets become operational, we will tap the overseas markets in the US, the UK, West Asia and Singapore. There are plans to set up 12 Revolution outlets overseas, he said.																								The company has 350 retail outlets across the country and has earned revenues of Rs 225 crore last year. 
